licenses/by-sa/3.0/"/> <link rel="canonical" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Creepiness"/> <link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//login.wikimedia.org"/> <link rel="dns-prefetch" href="//meta.wikimedia.org" /> <!--[if lt IE 9]><script src="/w/load.php?debug=false&amp;lang=en&amp;modules=html5shiv&amp;only=scripts&amp;skin=vector&amp;sync=1"></script><![endif]--> </head> <body class="mediawiki ltr sitedir-ltr mw-hide-empty-elt ns-0 ns-subject page-Creepiness rootpage-Creepiness skin-vector action-view">		<div id="mw-page-base" class="noprint"></div> 		<div id="mw-head-base" class="noprint"></div> 		<div id="content" class="mw-body" role="main"> 			<a id="top"></a> 			<div id="siteNotice" class="mw-body-content"><!-- CentralNotice --></div><div class="mw-indicators mw-body-content"> </div> <h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Creepiness</h1>			<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content"> 				<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>				<div id="contentSub"><span class="mw-redirectedfrom">  (Redirected from <a href="/w/index.php?title=Creepy&amp;redirect=no" class="mw-redirect" title="Creepy">Creepy</a>)</span></div> 								<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump"> 					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a> 				</div> 				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><table role="presentation" class="mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox" style="background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000"> <tr> <td class="mbox-image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/40px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.png" width="40" height="40" class="noviewer" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/60px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/99/Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg/80px-Wiktionary-logo-en-v2.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="391" data-file-height="391" /></td> <td class="mbox-text plainlist">Look up <i><b><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/creepy" class="extiw" title="wiktionary:creepy">creepy</a></b></i>&#160;or <i><b><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/eerie" class="extiw" title="wiktionary:eerie">eerie</a></b></i> in Wiktionary, the free dictionary.</td> </tr> </table> <div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Creepy_(disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig" title="Creepy (disambiguation)">Creepy (disambiguation)</a>.</div> <p><b>Creepiness</b> is the state of being <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/creepy" class="extiw" title="wikt:creepy">creepy</a>, or causing an unpleasant feeling of <a href="/wiki/Fear" title="Fear">fear</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/unease" class="extiw" title="wikt:unease">unease</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup> Certain traits or hobbies may make people seem creepy to others. The internet has been described as increasingly creepy.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Adam_Kotsko" title="Adam Kotsko">Adam Kotsko</a> has compared the modern conception of creepiness to the <a href="/wiki/Freudian" class="mw-redirect" title="Freudian">Freudian</a> concept of <i><a href="/wiki/Unheimlich" class="mw-redirect" title="Unheimlich">unheimlich</a></i>. The term has also been used to describe <a href="/wiki/Paranormal" title="Paranormal">paranormal</a> or <a href="/wiki/Supernatural" title="Supernatural">supernatural</a> phenomena.</p> <p></p> <div id="toc" class="toc"> <div class="toctitle"> <h2>Contents</h2> </div> <ul> <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#History_and_studies"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">History and studies</span></a></li> <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-2"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li> <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-3"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li> <li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-4"><a href="#Bibliography"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">Bibliography</span></a></li> </ul> </div> <p></p> <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History_and_studies">History and studies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Creepiness&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History and studies">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> <div class="thumb tright"> <div class="thumbinner" style="width:142px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Clown_chili_peppers.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Clown_chili_peppers.jpg/140px-Clown_chili_peppers.jpg" width="140" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Clown_chili_peppers.jpg/210px-Clown_chili_peppers.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bf/Clown_chili_peppers.jpg/280px-Clown_chili_peppers.jpg 2x" data-file-width="476" data-file-height="600" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"> <div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Clown_chili_peppers.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div> Clowns are thought by some as creepy</div> </div> </div> <p>The concept of creepiness has only recently been formally addressed in social marketing.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup></p> <p>A 2016 study by Francis McAndrew and Sara Koehnke from <a href="/wiki/Knox_College_(Illinois)" title="Knox College (Illinois)">Knox College (Illinois)</a> surveyed 1,342 people of all ages (1,029 females and 312 male) about what kind of traits the subjects found creepy if a friend was describing meeting someone new to them.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup> The study found that men were more likely to be seen as creepy than women. Females are more likely than males to perceive sexual threat from a creepy person. Unpredictability is an important component of creepiness. Also hobbies and occupations related to handling the dead, clowns, and <a href="/wiki/Bird_watching" class="mw-redirect" title="Bird watching">bird watching</a> were commonly thought as creepy.</p> <p>In the abstract the feeling of "creepiness" is subjective: for example some <a href="/wiki/Dolls" class="mw-redirect" title="Dolls">dolls</a> have been described as creepy.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup></p> <p>Part of the modern attribute of "creepiness" includes the feeling of social stalking and privacy invasions. For example the practice of <a href="/wiki/Real-time_ridesharing" title="Real-time ridesharing">ride share</a> service <a href="/wiki/Uber_(company)" title="Uber (company)">Uber</a> monitoring the post-ride activity of its passengers has been described as creepy.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup> In 2017 the company announced that they would be ending this practice. The term <i>creep</i> is typically applied to men rather than women.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup> An example of purported creepy behavior is that by the purity pledgers of the purity movement.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></p> <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Creepiness&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> <ul> <li><a href="/wiki/Social_skills" title="Social skills">Social skills</a></li> <li><a href="/wiki/Uncanny_valley" title="Uncanny valley">Uncanny valley</a></li> <li><a href="/wiki/Internet_privacy" title="Internet privacy">Internet privacy</a></li> </ul> <h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Creepiness&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2> <div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;"> <div class="mw-references-wrap"> <ol class="references"> <li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Pages, The Society. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2015/12/26/what-is-creepiness/">"What is "creepiness"? - Sociological Images"</a>. <i>thesocietypages.org</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=thesocietypages.org&amp;rft.atitle=What+is+%E2%80%9Ccreepiness%E2%80%9D%3F+-+Sociological+Images&amp;rft.aulast=Pages&amp;rft.aufirst=The+Society&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fthesocietypages.org%2Fsocimages%2F2015%2F12%2F26%2Fwhat-is-creepiness%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACreepiness" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li> <li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-age-of-creepiness">"The Age of Creepiness"</a>. <i>The New Yorker</i>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+Yorker&amp;rft.atitle=The+Age+of+Creepiness&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorker.com%2Fculture%2Fcultural-comment%2Fthe-age-of-creepiness&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACreepiness" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li> <li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Bikramjit Rishi, Subir Bandyopadhyay <i>Contemporary Issues in Social Media Marketing</i> 1317193989 2017 "In this chapter, we define creepiness and discuss how privacy and perceived creepiness differ. Then, we explain why creepiness matters and provide recommendations to minimize the negative effect of perceived creepiness on customer ..."</span></li> <li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">MacDonald, Fiona. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.sciencealert.com/how-creepy-are-you-scientists-have-published-the-first-definitive-measure-of-creepiness">"Scientists Have Published The First Definitive Study of Creepiness"</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Scientists+Have+Published+The+First+Definitive+Study+of+Creepiness&amp;rft.aulast=MacDonald&amp;rft.aufirst=Fiona&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sciencealert.com%2Fhow-creepy-are-you-scientists-have-published-the-first-definitive-measure-of-creepiness&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACreepiness" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li> <li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://mentalfloss.com/article/69472/what-creepiness">"What is 'Creepiness'?"</a>. 6 October 2015.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=What+is+%27Creepiness%27%3F&amp;rft.date=2015-10-06&amp;rft_id